 In this paper, the exogenous variation in the number of children is obtained
 by using the occurence of multiple births (twins) at first birth as an
 instrument.
 The authors argue that the comparison between women who gave birth to a
 single child at first birth and women who gave birth to twins at first
 birth teases out the causal effect of related to an extra child.
 Since the occurence of twins is exogenous, there is no danger that heterogenity
 in women preferences contaminates the estimated coefficients.
 The study finds that household size reduces female labour supply, but the
 effect is only temporary
